Time series forecasting 2 - Non stationary

Dataset: soya_oil data set for TS forecast.csv

Import necessary libraries
rm(list=ls())
library('forecast')
## Warning: package 'forecast' was built under R version 4.0.2
## Registered S3 method overwritten by 'quantmod':
##   method            from
##   as.zoo.data.frame zoo
library('tseries')
## Warning: package 'tseries' was built under R version 4.0.2


Dataset
data=read.csv("soya_oil data set for TS forecast.csv")
class(data) # dataframe
## [1] "data.frame"

Convert the data to timeseries:

data=ts(data$Dollar,start=1,end=128,frequency=4)
class(data) # time series
## [1] "ts"
# View(data)


Visualisations

Visualise the timeseries data:

plot(data,xlab='time',ylab='Soya Oil sales')

Visualizing diff(data):

dd <- diff(data)
plot(dd,ylab='Differenced Soya Oil Sales')

Visualizing log(data):

ld <- log10(data)
plot(ld,ylab='Differenced Log (Soya Oil Sales)')

Visualizing diff(log(data)):

ld <- log10(data)
dld <- diff(ld)
plot(dld,ylab='Differenced Log (Soya Oil Sales)')


Testing and plotting
adf.test(data)
## Warning in adf.test(data): p-value smaller than printed p-value
## 
##  Augmented Dickey-Fuller Test
## 
## data:  data
## Dickey-Fuller = -4.3437, Lag order = 7, p-value = 0.01
## alternative hypothesis: stationary

ACF and PACF plots + fitting ARIMA model

par(mfrow=c(1,2))
acf(ts(data),main="ACF Soya Oil Sales")
pacf(ts(data),main="PACF Soya Oil Sales")

ARIMAfit=auto.arima(data,ic="aic",trace=TRUE)

Forecasting 3 time periods with the fitted model

fc=forecast(ARIMAfit,level=c(95),h=3*12)
plot(fc)

summary(fc)
